2. Obey yourparencs] Here we have the matter of the precept. namely, obedience to be rendered to parents. The Greek word ὑπακόυετε, comprises two things3 a humble promptitude in receiving the orders of another, and a cheerful obedience in executing the same. Therefore it pertains to this obedience, to do what parents order, to learn what they teach, to correct and amend what they re- prove, and, in one word, to perform all outward deeds which may testify the internal affection of reverence and submission.
